ECI Explorer.Description: Explore different Economic Complexity indicators for Mexico.
ECI Explorer.ECI Subtitle: The Economic Complexity Index (ECI) measures the productive capacities of a locality (e.g. state or municipality) based on the presence of activities (e.g. employment, industries or exports) in that and other localities. The economic complexity of a locality predicts its income level, economic growth, inequality, and greenhouse gas emissions. The ECI can be estimated using data on exports, employment, patents, etc., so the estimates differ according to the data and the thresholds used. This economically complex explorer allows you to calculate the ECI with different data sources and thresholds.
ECI Explorer.ECI Title: What is the Economic Complexity Index (ECI)?
ECI Explorer.PCI Subtitle: The Product Complexity Index (PCI) is a measure of the complexity required to develop an economic activity (e.g. industry, product or occupation). Its value correlates with spatial concentration and income from economic activities. The PCI can be estimated with data on exports, employment, patents, etc. so their values ​​differ according to the data and thresholds used. This explorer allows you to calculate PCI with different thresholds and data sources.
ECI Explorer.PCI Title: What is the Product Complexity Index (PCI)?

welcome.title: Welcome to the Vizbuilder
welcome.text1: This tutorial will guide you through the steps on how to use DataMéxico's Vizbuilder.
welcome.text2: By following this tutorial, you will be able to find your data of interest and generate your own data tables and visualizations.

dataset.title: Select a data set
dataset.text1: First, select the category (and possibly subcategory) of data you are interested in.
dataset.text2: Then, select a data "cube" that you are interested in.

metrics.title: Metrics
metrics.text1: Select the metrics that you are interested in viewing. A Metric is a column of numeric data that will be displayed in the query results. You must select at least one to make a query.

columns.title: Columns
columns.text1: Next, select the fields you want to display in the columns of your data table. You must select at least one.

filters.title: Filters
filters.text1: You can filter the elements of each column that you want to display in the data table and visualization.
filters.text2: If you want all available elements to be displayed, you don't need to apply filters.

options.title: Query options
options.text1: You can change the default order or include parents levels using the query options panel.

execute.title: Generate the query
execute.text1: Run the query based on your selection of metrics and columns.

download.title: Download data
download.text1: You are able to download the information in JSON or CSV formats files.

dataTab.title: Data table
dataTab.text1: You can see the results of your query in a table.
dataTab.text2: Click on the name of each column to modify the order and format of the variables.

vizbuilderTab.title: Vizbuilder
vizbuilderTab.text1: You can see the results of your query in different types of visualizations.

downloadViz.title: Download your visualizations
downloadViz.text1: You can download the various visualizations generated based on your selection (SVG, PNG).

matrixTab.title: Matrix (pivot table)
matrixTab.text1: You can modify the fields you want to display in the columns and rows of your data table, and choose the format of your numeric variables.

apiTab.title: API
apiTab.text1: You can access the raw data programmatically using the DataMéxico API.

last.title: Let's get started!
last.text: You are ready to start exploring DataMéxico data and generate your own tables and visualizations.
